  "title": "Psychodynamics",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3e6985a831bbe362",
      "text": "If one tries to analyze or (re)construct the generating mechanisms for such a way of describing oneself and the rest of the world, as a psychoanalyst one inevitably ends up with the so-called defense mechanisms such as displacement, inversion into the opposite, projection, etc. It should be noted that here, too, the description of the psychic dynamic seems coherent, but naming it is problematic. It suggests a purpose, a goal, an intention, as if mental processes were carried out on the basis of the decisions of an acting subject. Furthermore, such designations invite a hasty evaluation, depending on whether defense is considered positive or negative.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "269c0f597924134d",
      "text": "It seems to make more sense to see such mechanisms as the result of self-organization processes. It is then not so much the conscious or unconscious wishes, fears or goals of an individual (which perhaps also ...) that become effective, but the logical requirements for the coherence of reality constructions. The \"defense\" mechanisms can then be seen more clearly as mechanisms of \"adaptation\" to the logic of one's own construction principles. In relation to the worldviews of the actors involved, it is possible to analyze which distinctions are related to each other and how contradictory or non-contradictory (in the logical meaning) the attributions of characteristics to the two sides of distinctions, to self and other descriptions, are. The so-called defense mechanisms can then be interpreted as a method for eliminating logical contradictions, paradoxes and conflicts.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "33670256a9391175",
      "text": "In war, such mechanisms seem to be coordinated among a large number of people in order to create the willingness to go to war in the first place. You have to imagine this as a kind of resonance phenomenon that leads to a synchronization, a \"swinging in the same rhythm\" of otherwise very differently structured, individual psychological processes. \"Imagine there's a war and nobody goes!\" was a slogan that could be seen sprayed on walls for a while. The fact that so many people are prepared to go to war, be it public or private, can only be explained by the fact that it seems sensible to them.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d28fc3be3afabf2a",
      "text": "How can a world (in the meaning outlined above) be constructed individually and collectively that makes warlike actions likely? From a psychoanalytical perspective, the projection of aggression should be mentioned here first and foremost. Wherever there are conflicting tendencies or desires in a system, there is the possibility of externalizing one side of the conflict, i.e. excluding it, splitting it off. Just as a bus traveling from Heidelberg to Hamburg is likely to be more peaceful if the group of people who want to go to Munich are put on the train to Munich at the next station. They don't even have to be put on the train, it is enough if they are thrown/let off the bus. The same principle can also organize the handling of feelings and emotions. For example, if a person or a group of people have very ambivalent feelings, this ambivalence can be eliminated by only experiencing one side of the conflicting feelings and attributing the other side to another person or group and projecting it onto them. The both/and nature of the feelings has become an either/or, their ambiguity has been successfully eliminated. One's own identity thus remains free of contradictions.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b48d1f708750b550",
      "text": "The more aggressive feelings can be directed against people or groups or social units that do not belong to the inside of the distinction (\"I\"/\"we\"), the more the respective system (the psyche, the social system) can be kept free of conflict. If one's own hatred, anger and all one's own \"evil\" desires and thoughts can be attributed to the enemy, then the self-description remains clearly \"pure\" and \"good\". Scapegoats can be slaughtered because they are ascribed all the negative characteristics from which one must free oneself in order to conform to the self-ideal. Such externalization mechanisms free individual experience and supra-individual communication from internal conflicts. The logical coherence of the psychological processes is confirmed, as is the cohesion of the group.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "606acaf0007b03df",
      "text": "A (common) external enemy also creates a sense of togetherness between people and groups who otherwise have nothing in common. However, it is a negative identity that is defined by the outside of the distinction, i.e. by the one against whom one distinguishes oneself. It is not an identity created by shared positive characteristics of the distinction (the inside of the distinction). This creates a de facto dependence on the enemy. Only he can ensure commonality.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9f103209c2465476",
      "text": "But war is also the solution to another problem: the lack of meaning and purpose in life. It promises participation in a greater \"cause\" that transcends the individual. It relativizes all the values that determine everyday life and therefore relieves us of our troubles. Closely linked to this question of meaning is the need to dissolve one's own limitations, the self-object boundaries, in a larger, social unit. The awareness of one's own smallness and insignificance can be overcome if one can identify with a larger unit, a group, a nation, etc. and its greatness.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e6a03e371d0b9585",
      "text": "It should be noted at this point that the psychodynamics of members of cults and sects are very similar to those of warriors. Cults also fulfill the function of giving their followers the mythical black-and-white or either-or orientation of us versus them."
