        "text": "How can a world (in the meaning outlined above) be constructed individually and collectively that makes warlike actions likely? From a psychoanalytical perspective, the projection of aggression should be mentioned here first and foremost. Wherever there are conflicting tendencies or desires in a system, there is the possibility of externalizing one side of the conflict, i.e. excluding it, splitting it off. Just as a bus traveling from Heidelberg to Hamburg is likely to be more peaceful if the group of people who want to go to Munich are put on the train to Munich at the next station. They don't even have to be put on the train, it is enough if they are thrown/let off the bus. The same principle can also organize the handling of feelings and emotions. For example, if a person or a group of people have very ambivalent feelings, this ambivalence can be eliminated by only experiencing one side of the conflicting feelings and attributing the other side to another person or group and projecting it onto them. The both/and nature of the feelings has become an either/or, their ambiguity has been successfully eliminated. One's own identity thus remains free of contradictions.\n"
